n the answer. In this groundbreaking book, Andrew Lo transforms the debate with a powerful new framework in which rationality and irrationality coexist—the Adaptive Markets Hypothesis. Drawing on psychology, evolutionary biology, neuroscience, artificial intelligence, and other fields, Adaptive Markets shows that the theory of market efficiency is incomplete. When markets are unstable, investors react instinctively, creating inefficiencies for others to exploit. Lo’s new paradigm explains how financial evolution shapes behavior and markets at the speed of thought—a fact revealed by swings between stability and crisis, profit and loss, and innovation and regulation. An ambitious new answer to fundamental questions about economics and investing, Adaptive Markets is essential reading for anyone who wants to understand how markets really work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEfficient market theory. 0aInvestments-Psychological aspects. 0aStock exchanges. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Finance / General.2bisacsh  aAdaptive market hypothesis.  aArbitrage.  aAsset.  aBank run.  aBank.  aBehavior.  aBehavioral economics.  aBiology.  aBroker-dealer.  aCalculation.  aCareer.  aCentral bank.  aCompetition.  aCryptocurrency.  aCurrency.  aCustomer.  aDebt.  aDecision-making.  aEconomics.  aEconomist.  aEcosystem.  aEfficient-market hypothesis.  aEmployment.  aEntrepreneurship.  aEquity Market.  aEvolution.  aFinance.  aFinancial crisis of 2007–08.  aFinancial crisis.  aFinancial economics.  aFinancial innovation.  aFinancial institution.  aFinancial services.  aFinancial technology.  aForecasting.  aFraud.  aFunding.  aHedge Fund Manager.  aHedge fund.  aHeuristic.  aHomo economicus.  aHuman behavior.  aIncentive.  aIncome.  aInsider.  aIns